# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: delaunay-triangulation-algo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] In computational geometry, the **Bowyer–Watson algorithm** is a method for computing the Delaunay triangulation of a finite set of points in any number of dimensions.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] The algorithm can be also used to obtain a Voronoi diagram of the points, which is the dual graph of the Delaunay triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] The Bowyer–Watson algorithm is an incremental algorithm.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] It works by adding points, one at a time, to a valid Delaunay triangulation of a subset of the desired points.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] After every insertion, any triangles whose circumcircles contain the new point are deleted, leaving a star-shaped polygonal hole which is then re-triangulated using the new point.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] By using the connectivity of the triangulation to efficiently locate triangles to remove, the algorithm can take *O(N log N)* operations to triangulate N points, although special degenerate cases exist where this goes up to *O(N2)*.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] The algorithm is sometimes known just as the **Bowyer Algorithm** or the **Watson Algorithm**.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] Adrian Bowyer and David Watson devised it independently of each other at the same time, and each published a paper on it in the same issue of *The Computer Journal* (see below).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] The following pseudocode describes a basic implementation of the Bowyer–Watson algorithm.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] Efficiency can be improved in a number of ways.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] For example, the triangle connectivity can be used to locate the triangles which contain the new point in their circumcircle, without having to check all of the triangles - by doing so we can decrease time complexity to $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] Pre-computing the circumcircles can save time at the expense of additional memory usage.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/bowyer-watson-algorithm] And if the points are uniformly distributed, sorting them along a space filling Hilbert curve prior to insertion can also speed point location.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] It can be computed efficiently and has applications in geographic information systems and in mesh generation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] The input to the constrained Delaunay triangulation problem is a planar straight-line graph, a set of points and non-crossing line segments in the plane.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] The constrained Delaunay triangulation of this input is a triangulation of its convex hull, including all of the input segments as edges, and using only the vertices of the input.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] For every additional edge e added to this input to make it into a triangulation, there should exist a circle through the endpoints of e , such that any vertex interior to the circle is blocked from visibility from at least one endpoint of e by a segment of the input.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] This generalizes the defining property of two-dimensional Delaunay triangulations of points, that each edge have a circle through its two endpoints containing no other vertices.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] A triangulation satisfying these properties always exists.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] Several algorithms for computing constrained Delaunay triangulations of planar straight-line graphs in time $O(n\log n)$ are known.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] The constrained Delaunay triangulation of a simple polygon can be constructed in linear time.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] In topographic surveying, one constructs a triangulation from points shot in the field.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] If an edge of the triangulation crosses a river, the resulting surface does not accurately model the path of the river.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] So one draws **break lines** along rivers, edges of roads, mountain ridges, and the like.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] The break lines are used as constraints when constructing the triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/constrained-delaunay-triangulation] Constrained Delaunay triangulation can also be used in Delaunay refinement methods for mesh generation, as a way to force the mesh to conform with the domain boundaries as it is being refined.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] When doing computer simulations such as computational fluid dynamics, one starts with a model such as a 2D outline of a wing section.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] The input to a 2D finite element method needs to be in the form of triangles that fill all space, and each triangle to be filled with one kind of material – in this example, either "air" or "wing".
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Long, skinny triangles cannot be simulated accurately.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] The simulation time is generally proportional to the number of triangles, and so one wants to minimize the number of triangles, while still using enough triangles to give reasonably accurate results – typically by using an unstructured grid.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] The computer uses a meshing algorithm to convert the polygonal model into triangles suitable for the finite element method.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] The algorithm begins with a constrained Delaunay triangulation of the input vertices.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] At each step, the circumcenter of a poor-quality triangle is inserted into the triangulation with one exception: If the circumcenter lies on the opposite side of an input segment as the poor quality triangle, the midpoint of the segment is inserted.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Moreover, any previously inserted circumcenters inside the diametral ball of the original segment (before it is split) are removed from the triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Circumcenter insertion is repeated until no poor-quality triangles exist.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] The algorithm begins with a Delaunay triangulation of the input vertices and then consists of two main operations.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] These operations are repeated until no poor-quality triangles exist and all segments are not encroached.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Without modification Ruppert's algorithm is guaranteed to terminate and generate a quality mesh for non-acute input and any poor-quality threshold less than about 20.7 degrees.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] To relax these restrictions various small improvements have been made.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] By relaxing the quality requirement near small input angles, the algorithm can be extended to handle any straight-line input.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Curved input can also be meshed using similar techniques.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Ruppert's algorithm can be naturally extended to three dimensions, however its output guarantees are somewhat weaker due to the sliver type tetrahedron.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] An extension of Ruppert's algorithm in two dimensions is implemented in the freely available Triangle package.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] Two variants of Ruppert's algorithm in this package are guaranteed to terminate for a poor-quality threshold of about 26.5 degrees.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] In practice these algorithms are successful for poor-quality thresholds over 30 degrees.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-refinement] However, examples are known which cause the algorithm to fail with a threshold greater than 29.06 degrees.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This maximizes the size of the smallest angle in any of the triangles, and tends to avoid sliver triangles.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The triangulation is named after Boris Delaunay for his work on it from 1934.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] If the points all lie on a straight line, the notion of triangulation becomes degenerate and there is no Delaunay triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] By considering circumscribed spheres, the notion of Delaunay triangulation extends to three and higher dimensions.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Generalizations are possible to metrics other than Euclidean distance.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] However, in these cases a Delaunay triangulation is not guaranteed to exist or be unique.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation with all the circumcircles and their centers (in red).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation of a discrete point set **P** in general position corresponds to the dual graph of the Voronoi diagram for **P**.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The circumcenters of Delaunay triangles are the vertices of the Voronoi diagram.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] In the 2D case, the Voronoi vertices are connected via edges, that can be derived from adjacency-relationships of the Delaunay triangles: If two triangles share an edge in the Delaunay triangulation, their circumcenters are to be connected with an edge in the Voronoi tesselation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] For a set **P** of points in the (d-dimensional) Euclidean space, a **Delaunay triangulation** is a triangulation DT(**P**) such that no point in **P** is inside the circum-hypersphere of any d-simplex in DT(**P**).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] It is known that there exists a unique Delaunay triangulation for **P** if **P** is a set of points in *general position*; that is, the affine hull of **P** is d-dimensional and no set of *d* + 2 points in **P** lie on the boundary of a ball whose interior does not intersect **P**.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The problem of finding the Delaunay triangulation of a set of points in d-dimensional Euclidean space can be converted to the problem of finding the convex hull of a set of points in (*d* + 1)-dimensional space.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] As the convex hull is unique, so is the triangulation, assuming all facets of the convex hull are simplices.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Nonsimplicial facets only occur when *d* + 2 of the original points lie on the same d-hypersphere, i.e., the points are not in general position.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Let n be the number of points and d the number of dimensions.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] From the above properties an important feature arises: Looking at two triangles △*ABD*, △*BCD* with the common edge BD (see figures), if the sum of the angles α + γ ≤ 180°, the triangles meet the Delaunay condition.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This is an important property because it allows the use of a *flipping* technique.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This operation is called a *flip*, and can be generalised to three and higher dimensions.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Many algorithms for computing Delaunay triangulations rely on fast operations for detecting when a point is within a triangle's circumcircle and an efficient data structure for storing triangles and edges.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] When A, B, C are sorted in a counterclockwise order, this determinant is positive only if D lies inside the circumcircle.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] As mentioned above, if a triangle is non-Delaunay, we can flip one of its edges.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This leads to a straightforward algorithm: construct any triangulation of the points, and then flip edges until no triangle is non-Delaunay.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately, this can take Ω(*n*2) edge flips.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] While this algorithm can be generalised to three and higher dimensions, its convergence is not guaranteed in these cases, as it is conditioned to the connectedness of the underlying flip graph: this graph is connected for two-dimensional sets of points, but may be disconnected in higher dimensions.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The most straightforward way of efficiently computing the Delaunay triangulation is to repeatedly add one vertex at a time, retriangulating the affected parts of the graph.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] When a vertex v is added, we split in three the triangle that contains v, then we apply the flip algorithm.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Done naïvely, this will take O(*n*) time: we search through all the triangles to find the one that contains v, then we potentially flip away every triangle.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] If we insert vertices in random order, it turns out (by a somewhat intricate proof) that each insertion will flip, on average, only O(1) triangles – although sometimes it will flip many more.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This still leaves the point location time to improve.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] We can store the history of the splits and flips performed: each triangle stores a pointer to the two or three triangles that replaced it.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] To find the triangle that contains v, we start at a root triangle, and follow the pointer that points to a triangle that contains v, until we find a triangle that has not yet been replaced.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] On average, this will also take O(log *n*) time.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Over all vertices, then, this takes O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] While the technique extends to higher dimensions (as proved by Edelsbrunner and Shah), the runtime can be exponential in the dimension even if the final Delaunay triangulation is small.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The Bowyer–Watson algorithm provides another approach for incremental construction.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] It gives an alternative to edge flipping for computing the Delaunay triangles containing a newly inserted vertex.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately the flipping-based algorithms are generally hard to parallelize, since adding some certain point (e.g. the center point of a wagon wheel) can lead to up to O(*n*) consecutive flips.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Blelloch et al. proposed another version of incremental algorithm based on rip-and-tent, which is practical and highly parallelized with polylogarithmic span.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer algorithm for triangulations in two dimensions was developed by Lee and Schachter and improved by Guibas and Stolfi and later by Dwyer.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] In this algorithm, one recursively draws a line to split the vertices into two sets.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation is computed for each set, and then the two sets are merged along the splitting line.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Using some clever tricks, the merge operation can be done in time O(*n*), so the total running time is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] For certain types of point sets, such as a uniform random distribution, by intelligently picking the splitting lines the expected time can be reduced to O(*n* log log *n*) while still maintaining worst-case performance.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer paradigm to performing a triangulation in d dimensions is presented in "DeWall: A fast divide and conquer Delaunay triangulation algorithm in E*d*" by P.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The divide and conquer algorithm has been shown to be the fastest DT generation technique sequentially.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Sweephull is a hybrid technique for 2D Delaunay triangulation that uses a radially propagating sweep-hull, and a flipping algorithm.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The sweep-hull is created sequentially by iterating a radially-sorted set of 2D points, and connecting triangles to the visible part of the convex hull, which gives a non-overlapping triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] One can build a convex hull in this manner so long as the order of points guarantees no point would fall within the triangle.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] But, radially sorting should minimize flipping by being highly Delaunay to start.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] This is then paired with a final iterative triangle flipping step.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The Euclidean minimum spanning tree of a set of points is a subset of the Delaunay triangulation of the same points, and this can be exploited to compute it efficiently.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] For modelling terrain or other objects given a point cloud, the Delaunay triangulation gives a nice set of triangles to use as polygons in the model.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] In particular, the Delaunay triangulation avoids narrow triangles (as they have large circumcircles compared to their area).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations can be used to determine the density or intensity of points samplings by means of the Delaunay tessellation field estimator (DTFE).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations are often used to generate meshes for space-discretised solvers such as the finite element method and the finite volume method of physics simulation, because of the angle guarantee and because fast triangulation algorithms have been developed.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Typically, the domain to be meshed is specified as a coarse simplicial complex; for the mesh to be numerically stable, it must be refined, for instance by using Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The increasing popularity of finite element method and boundary element method techniques increases the incentive to improve automatic meshing algorithms.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] However, all of these algorithms can create distorted and even unusable grid elements.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Fortunately, several techniques exist which can take an existing mesh and improve its quality.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] For example, smoothing (also referred to as mesh refinement) is one such method, which repositions nodes to minimize element distortion.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] The stretched grid method allows the generation of pseudo-regular meshes that meet the Delaunay criteria easily and quickly in a one-step solution.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/delaunay-triangulation] Constrained Delaunay triangulation has found applications in path planning in automated driving and topographic surveying.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] In computational geometry, a **Pitteway triangulation** is a point set triangulation in which the nearest neighbor of any point *p* within the triangulation is one of the vertices of the triangle containing *p*.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Alternatively, it is a Delaunay triangulation in which each internal edge crosses its dual Voronoi diagram edge.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Pitteway triangulations are named after Michael Pitteway, who studied them in 1973.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Not every point set supports a Pitteway triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] When such a triangulation exists it is a special case of the Delaunay triangulation, and consists of the union of the Gabriel graph and convex hull.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] The concept of a Pitteway triangulation was introduced by Pitteway (1973).
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] See also McLain (1976), who writes "An optimal partition is one in which, for any point within any triangle, that point lies at least as close to one of the vertices of that triangle as to any other data point." The name "Pitteway triangulation" was given by Okabe et al.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Gold (1978) points out that not every point set supports a Pitteway triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] For instance, any triangulation of a regular pentagon includes a central isosceles triangle such that a point *p* near the midpoint of one of the triangle sides has its nearest neighbor outside the triangle.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] When a Pitteway triangulation exists, the midpoint of each edge interior to the triangulation must have the two edge endpoints as its nearest neighbors, for any other neighbor would violate the Pitteway property for nearby points in one of the two adjacent triangles.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Thus, a circle having that edge as diameter must be empty of vertices, so the Pitteway triangulation consists of the Gabriel graph together with the convex hull of the point set.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Conversely, when the Gabriel graph and convex hull together form a triangulation, it is a Pitteway triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] Since all Gabriel graph and convex hull edges are part of the Delaunay triangulation, a Pitteway triangulation, when it exists, is unique for points in general position and coincides with the Delaunay triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] However, point sets with no Pitteway triangulation will still have a Delaunay triangulation.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] In the Pitteway triangulation, each edge *pq* either belongs to the convex hull or crosses the edge of the Voronoi diagram that separates the cells containing *p* and *q*.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] In some references this property is used to define a Pitteway triangulation, as a Delaunay triangulation in which all internal Delaunay edges cross their dual Voronoi edges.
[src:delaunay-triangulation-algo/pitteway-triangulation] However, a Pitteway triangulation may include convex hull edges that do not cross their duals.
